| alma_mater = 
}}'''Gordon Lloyd Chavunduka''' (c.16 August 1931 &ndash; 11 January 2013) was a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[sociology|sociologist]] and traditional healer. 

==Biography==
He served as a member of [[Abel Muzorewa]]'s delegation to the 1979 [[Lancaster House Agreement|Lancaster House Conference]] that led to Zimbabwe's independence.<ref>{{cite book| last = Martin |first = D. |authorlink = |author2=Johnson, P.| title = The struggle for Zimbabwe |publisher = Faber and Faber | year =1981 |location =Boston | pages =400 | url =| doi= | id =|isbn = 978-0-85345-599-8}}</ref> He has published several books on traditional medicine.<ref>{{cite book| last= Chavunduka|first= G.| authorlink =Gordon Chavunduka| title = Interaction of folk and scientific beliefs in Shona medical practices. |year=1972|publisher=Ph.D. thesis, University of London}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last = Chavunduka| first= G.| authorlink=Gordon Chavunduka| title=Traditional Healers and the Shona Patient|year=1978|location= Gwelo|publisher= Mambo}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last = Last| first = M. L.| authorlink =|author2=Chavunduka, G. |title =The Professionalization of African Medicine: Ambiguities and Definitions |publisher= Manchester University Press| year=1988 | location=Manchester | pages=308| url= | doi= | id =| isbn=978-0-7190-2252-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Chavunduka| first=G.| authorlink=Gordon Chavunduka| title=Traditional medicine in modern Zimbabwe| publisher=University of Zimbabwe Publications| year=1994| location=Harare| pages=115| url=http://www.kew.org/kbd/detailedresult.do?id=107336| doi=| id=| isbn=978-0-908307-40-1}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Chavunduka| first =G.| authorlink=Gordon Chavunduka| title=Traditional Healers and the Shona Patient| publisher=Mambo Press| year=1978 | location= Harare| pages = 139| url =| doi = | id =| asin = B0000EDYZT}}</ref>

Prof. Chavunduka was [[List of principals of the University of Zimbabwe|Vice Chancellor]] of the [[University of Zimbabwe]] from 1992 to 1996.<ref name="aboutuz">{{cite web|last=University of Zimbabwe|first=|authorlink=University of Zimbabwe|title=About UZ|url=http://www.uz.ac.zw/information/uz.html|accessdate=2009-01-02|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212230253/http://www.uz.ac.zw/information/uz.html|archivedate=2008-12-12|df=}}</ref> After his retirement from the university, he served as president of the Zimbabwe National Traditional Healers Association.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thezimbabwean.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17576&Itemid=108|title=Holy Water Is Serious Business|date=2 January 2009|work=The Zimbabwean|accessdate=2009-01-04|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923161530/http://www.thezimbabwean.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content|archivedate=23 September 2010|df=}}</ref> He was a great influence to [[Christopher Chetsanga]].

==Death==
Chavunduka died on 11 January 2013 at the age of 82 in Harare, after a short illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nehandaradio.com/2013/01/11/professor-gordon-chavunduka-dies/|title=MDC-T senior official Professor Gordon Chavunduka, a former Vice Chancellor of the University of Zimbabwe and president of the Zimbabwe National Traditional Healers’ Association (ZINATHA) has died|publisher=nehandaradio.com|date=2013-01-11|accessdate=2013-01-13}}</ref>

