{{About||the American jurist|Otto Bock (jurist)|the Danish athlete|Otto Bock (athlete)}} {{use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}
{{Infobox Company | name = Otto Bock HealthCare GmbH | logo = Otto Bock logo.svg | logo_size = 200px | type = [[GmbH]] | genre = | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = [[Berlin]], Germany ({{start date| 13 January 1919}}) | founder = Otto Bock | defunct = | location_city = [[Duderstadt]] | location_country = Germany | location = | locations = | area_served = | key_people = {{Interlanguage link multi|Hans Georg Näder|de}} | industry = Orthopaedic | products = [[wheelchair]], [[prosthetic]], artificial limbs | services = | revenue = €771 million (2015) | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = 6,300 (2015) | parent = | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = [http://www.ottobock.com/ www.ottobock.com] | footnotes = | intl = }}
'''Ottobock''' is a German [[prosthetic]]s company situated in [[Duderstadt]]. It has been responsible for several innovations in prosthetics, including the [[C-Leg]], a computerized knee that adaptively varies its passive resistance to suit the patients' different walking gaits, and the [[Michelangelo Hand]], a fully articulated robotic hand prosthesis. Ottobock has been a partner to the [[Paralympic Games]] since 1988, and an international worldwide partner to the [[International Paralympic Committee]] since 2005. In 2016, the partnership was extended until the end of 2020.
==History== Ottobock was founded in Berlin as Orthopädische Industrie GmbH in 1919 by its namesake prosthetist, Otto Bock. It was created in response to the large number of injured veterans from [[World War I]]. Prostheses handmade by craftsmen could not keep up with demand. Bock's idea was to create components through industrial processes that could be supplied to prosthetists. This marked the beginning of a new industry. The political situation in post-war Berlin was unstable, and soon after the company was founded, it moved to [[Königsee]] in [[Thuringia]]. Over the following two decades, the company expanded to employ over 600 people.<ref name="History">{{cite web |url=http://www.ottobock.com/en/company/history/ |title=History: over 90 years of progress and tradition |publisher=Otto Bock |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref>
[[File:Science Center Medizintechnik Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|Science Center Medizintechnik in Berlin]] After [[World War II]], Königsee lay within the Russian-occupied [[East Germany]]. The company property and assets there were [[expropriated]] in 1948. However, Max and Maria Näder, Bock's son-in-law and daughter, had established an office in [[Duderstadt]] in [[Lower Saxony]], initially as a sales office for the zones of Germany [[Allied-occupied Germany|occupied by the Western powers]]. In 1947, Max Näder became the managing director of the newly formed Otto Bock Orthopädische Industrie KG. Otto Bock died in 1953.<ref name="History" />
The company has been responsible for several innovations in prosthetics. As wood was in short supply in the early post-war years, it pioneered the use of [[polyurethane]] to manufacture prosthetics.<ref name="History" /> Otto Bock Kunststoff was founded in 1953 to produce plastic prosthetics. By 2016, it employed 423 people and anticipated revenues of €127 million.<ref name="History" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://plasticker.de/news/shownews.php?nr=28819 |publisher=Plasticker |title=Ottobock Kunststoff: Inhaber prüft strategische Optionen - Veräußerung oder strategische Partnerschaften möglich |language=German |date=14 October 2016 |access-date=19 October 2016 }}</ref> Ottobock developed the pyramid adapter, a highly adjustable linkage for prosthetic parts. In 1997, it introduced the [[C-Leg]], a computerized knee that adaptively varies its passive resistance to suit the patients' different walking gaits. It was the world's first fully microprocessor-controlled leg prosthesis system, and transformed the company into a vendor of highly complex mobility systems. The C-Leg was followed by the [[Michelangelo Hand]], a fully articulated robotic hand prosthesis, and the mechatronic C-Brace orthotronic mobility system.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ottobockus.com/c-leg.html |title=C-Leg 4 above knee prosthetic leg |publisher=Ottobock USA |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://en.red-dot.org/2246.html | title = Ottobock Healthcare wins the red dot: best of the best three times in this year’s red dot award: product design| accessdate=8 May 2009}}</ref> Ottobock developed the waterproof Genium X3 knee in cooperation with the [[United States Department of Defense]] to allow amputee soldiers to return to duty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/luxury-prosthetics |title=The 'Maserati of Microprocessor Prosthetics' Costs $120,000 |work=[[Motherboard (website)|Motherboard]] |access-date=19 October 2016}}</ref>
In 1958, a US-based corporate headquarters was established in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]] under the name Ottobock. In March 2014, the company announced it would relocate its North American headquarters to [[Austin, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2014/03/31/german-health-care-manufacturer-to-bring-us.html|title=German Health Care Manufacturer to Bring U.S. Headquarters, 110 Jobs to Austin|publisher=Austin Business Journal|first=Robert|last=Grattan|date=31 March 2014|access-date=23 August 2016}}</ref> The logistics facility relocated to [[Louisville, Kentucky]], and manufacturing moved to [[Salt Lake City, Utah]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oandp.com/articles/NEWS_2014-01-23_01.asp |newspaper=The O&P Edge |title=Ottobock Relocating HQ to Texas, Other Divisions to Utah, Kentucky|date=23 January 2014 |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://lermagazine.com/market-mechanics/ottobock-moves-operations-to-louisville|title=Ottobock moves operations to Louisville |newspaper=Lower Extremity Review |first= Emily |last=Delzell |date=April 2014 |p=66 |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref> The US company was its first foreign branch. By 2016, it had branches in 45 different countries.<ref name="History" /> Sycor was established as a wholly owned subsidiary in 1998. By 2015, it had 520 employees, and annual revenues of €66.7 million.<ref name="Sycor">{{cite web |url=http://de.sycor-group.com/corporate/unternehmen/sycor-firmengruppe/zahlen-daten-fakten/ |title=Umsatz- und Mitarbeiterzahlen von Sycor |language=German |publisher=Sycor |access-date=13 October 2016}}</ref>
Professor Hans Georg Näder became head of the company in 1990. In 1992, after the [[Fall of the Berlin Wall]] and the subsequent [[German reunification]], the Näder family re-purchased the land in Königsee that had been expropriated in 1948, and established a new wheelchair manufacturing facility and logistics centre there.<ref name="History" /> A medical science centre ({{lang-de|Science Center Medizintechnik}}) was built by the company in Berlin in 2009 to celebrate 90 years since its foundation.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.artcom.de/index.php?lang=en&option=com_acnews&task=view&id=320&Itemid=136&page=0 | title = A Science Center for Ottobock at Potsdamer Platz| accessdate=8 May 2009}}</ref> Max Näder died that year at the age of 94.<ref name="History" /> By 2015, with a work force of 6,300 and annual sales of €771 million, the company was valued at €2.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://de.reuters.com/article/deutschland-ottobock-idDEKCN0PK1QY20150710 |title=Prothesen-Weltmarktführer Otto Bock will an die Börse |language=German |date=10 July 2015 |publisher=Reuters |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref> In February 2017 Ottobock acquired [[BeBionic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ottobock kauft BeBionic von Steeper |url=http://www.goettinger-tageblatt.de/Welt/Wirtschaft/Regional/Ottobock-kauft-BeBionic-von-Steeper|newspaper=Göttinger Tageblatt|accessdate=1 March 2017|date=2 February 2017 |first=Bernard |last=Marks |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ottobock acquires BeBionic from Steeper|url=http://www.healio.com/orthotics-prosthetics/industry-news/news/online/%7Be973ffbd-3c94-4a48-a400-7481c7af32df%7D/ottobock-acquires-bebionic-from-steeper|website=www.healio.com|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref>
== Paralympic Games == [[File:Ottobock at the Rio Paralympic Games (1).jpg|thumb|right|An Ottobock technician repairs a wheelchair at the [[2016 Paralympic Games]] in Rio de Janeiro]] Ottobock has been a partner to the [[Paralympic Games]] since 1988, and an international worldwide partner to the [[International Paralympic Committee]] (IPC) since 2005.<ref name="Fact Sheet">{{cite web |url=http://www.ottobock.com/media/local-media/paralympics/images/rio-page-2016/documents/ottobock-the-paralympic-games-factsheet_final.pdf |title=Ottobock Paralympic Games Fact Sheet |publisher=Ottobock |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref> The [[2016 Paralympic Games]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] was the 13th games at which it provided technical services.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/ottobock-announced-official-provider-rio-2016-paralympic-games |title=Ottobock announced as the Official Provider for the Rio 2016 Paralympic Games |date=8 September 2014 |publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]] |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref> This involved shipping {{convert|18|t}} of equipment, including 250 items classed as hazardous good or dangerous chemicals, and 15,000 spare parts, including 1,100 wheelchair tyres, 70 running blades and 300 prosthetic feet, {{convert|300|km}} from Duderstadt to the port at [[Bremerhaven]], {{convert|10100|km}} by sea to [[Port of Santos|Santos]], and then {{convert|500|km}} by road to Rio de Janeiro.<ref name="Today">{{cite web |url=http://www.ottobock.com/en/paralympics/rio-2016/ |title=Today in the Ottobock Repair Service Centers |publisher=Ottobock |access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref> At Seoul in 1988, four Ottobock technicians carried out 350 repairs;<ref name="Fact Sheet"/> in Rio de Janeiro in 2016, 100 technicians from 29 countries speaking 26 languages carried out 3,361 repairs for 1,162 athletes, including 2,745 repairs to wheelchairs, 438 to prosthetics, and 178 to orthodics.<ref name="Today" />
By 2016, Ottobock was the IPC's longest-serving partner. In Rio on 10 September, the IPC's president, Sir [[Philip Craven]], announced that Ottobock had agreed to extend its world-wide partnership to the end of 2020, encompassing the [[2020 Paralympic Games]] in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/ottobock-ipc-extend-partnership-until-end-2020 |title=Ottobock, IPC extend partnership until the end of 2020 |date=10 September 2016 |access-date=19 October 2016 }}</ref>
